DOMAIN_OVERVIEW:
The extended mind thesis (EMT), introduced by Clark and Chalmers in 1998, challenges traditional cognitive science by arguing that cognitive processes can extend beyond the brain to include aspects of the physical and social environment. The thesis distinguishes itself from standard externalism about mental content by proposing active externalism - the view that external resources can play constitutive (not merely causal) roles in cognition when they are coupled with internal processes in the right way. The debate centers on the parity principle, which holds that if external processes perform the same functional role as internal processes, they should count as genuinely cognitive.

The literature divides into proponents who develop and defend various versions of EMT (Clark, Rowlands, Menary, Wilson) and critics who challenge the coupling-constitution inference and argue for principled boundaries to cognition (Adams and Aizawa, Rupert). Key theoretical issues include the distinction between vehicle and content externalism, the role of functionalist and externalist commitments, the proper individuation of cognitive systems, and whether EMT represents a genuine alternative to computational-representational theories or merely extends their scope.

RELEVANCE_TO_PROJECT:
This domain provides the essential theoretical foundation for understanding how cognitive processes might extend into external resources. The debates about parity, coupling, and constitution directly inform questions about when external tools genuinely become part of cognitive processes versus merely supporting them. The functionalist framework underlying EMT connects to questions about what makes cognitive offloading genuinely cognitive rather than merely instrumental.

NOTABLE_GAPS:
Limited coverage of the distinction between different motivations for EMT (phenomenological vs functional). Few papers addressing the relationship between EMT and empirical research on cognitive offloading. The role of learning and skill acquisition in establishing cognitive extension remains underexplored in this foundational literature. Six entries lack abstracts (Rupert 2004, Wilson 2005, Farkas 2011, Theiner 2011, Farina & Levin 2021, Farina & Lavazza 2022) - marked INCOMPLETE and excluded from synthesis but retained for reference completeness.

SYNTHESIS_GUIDANCE:
