DOMAIN_OVERVIEW:
The parity principle, introduced by Clark and Chalmers (1998), holds that if an external process plays the same functional role as an internal one, it should count as cognitive. This domain encompasses the principle's formulation, major philosophical critiques, and proposed alternatives. The central debate revolves around whether functional parity is sufficient for cognitive status or whether additional criteria are needed.

Critics like Adams and Aizawa (2001) argue that parity leads to "cognitive bloat" and that genuine cognition requires non-derived content. Rupert (2004, 2009) challenges the principle via his Hypothesis of Embedded Cognition (HEC), proposing that cognitive systems are individuated by causal integration rather than parity. Sprevak (2009) and Wheeler (2010) explore whether functionalism entails extended mind, while Wheeler (2011) seeks conceptual clarification of what parity actually requires.

