  CORE ARGUMENT: Examines extended mind thesis in relation to personal identity and agency, arguing that EMT threatens the unity and persistence of persons. Proposes a modest alternative: subpersonal cognitive states can have nonbiological parts while persons remain bounded by bodies. Distinguishes between transitory couplings and enduring subjects of experience. Argues that EMT must be constrained to preserve agency and moral responsibility.

  RELEVANCE: Baker's concerns about personal identity connect to questions about whether cognitive offloading threatens the integrity of the cognitive subject. If minds extend through temporary couplings with external resources, questions arise about unity and persistence of cognitive agency. This bears on whether extensive offloading might undermine rather than enhance cognitive functioning by fragmenting cognitive systems.

