  unnecessary complexity).

  RELEVANCE: This paper directly addresses a tension central to cognitive
  offloading: external resources can enhance cognition but may simultaneously
  undermine the cognitive effort needed for skill development. The
  scaffolding framework offers principles for designing offloading that
  supports rather than supplants cognitive growth. This is practically
  relevant to understanding when and how cognitive offloading benefits
  versus harms cognitive development.

  POSITION: Proposes Enhanced Cognitive Scaffolding to resolve tensions
  between cognitive extension and cognitive development in AI systems.
  },
  keywords = {cognitive-scaffolding, AI-integration, cognitive-development, Medium, INCOMPLETE, no-abstract}
}

@article{trybulec2015extended,
  author = {Trybulec, Barbara},
  title = {Extended Cognitive System and Epistemic Subject},
  journal = {Studies in Logic, Grammar and Rhetoric},
  year = {2015},
  volume = {40},
  pages = {111--128},
  doi = {10.1515/slgr-2015-0006},
  note = {
  CORE ARGUMENT: Trybulec analyzes the epistemic subject within extended
  cognitive systems, contrasting first-wave (Clark-Chalmers) and second-wave
  (Menary's Cognitive Integration) arguments. She argues Menary's position
  is more intuitive and fruitful than parity-based approaches and is
  compatible with Greco's virtue reliabilism. The epistemic subject is
  constituted by cognitive character comprising integrated abilities and
  processes, some of which are extended through manipulation of external
  informational structures. These constitute epistemic practices governed by
  culturally embedded norms. The epistemic subject is not extended through
  causal coupling but through practices that transform cognitive abilities.

  RELEVANCE: This paper connects cognitive integration to virtue
  epistemology, addressing how extended cognitive practices relate to
  epistemic responsibility and intellectual character. The distinction
  between extension through coupling versus transformation through practices
  is relevant to understanding whether cognitive offloading changes
  epistemic agency. The normative dimension highlights that offloading
  occurs within culturally shaped epistemic practices.

  POSITION: Integrates Menary's cognitive integration with virtue
  epistemology, emphasizing transformation through epistemic practices.
  },
  keywords = {cognitive-integration, virtue-epistemology, epistemic-subject, Medium},
  abstract = {Abstract The concept of an extended cognitive system is central to contemporary studies of cognition. In the paper I analyze the place of the epistemic subject within the extended cognitive system. Is it extended as well? In answering this question I focus on the differences between the first and the second wave of arguments for the extended mind thesis. I argue that the position of Cognitive Integration represented by Richard Menary is much more intuitive and fruitful in analyses of cognition and knowledge than the early argument formulated by Andy Clark and David Chalmers. Cognitive Integration is compatible with virtue epistemology of John Greco’s agent reliabilism. The epistemic subject is constituted by its cognitive character composed of an integrated set of cognitive abilities and processes. Some of these processes are extended, they are a manipulation of external informational structures and, as such, they constitute epistemic practices. Epistemic practices are normative; to conduct them correctly the epistemic subject needs to obey epistemic norms embedded in the cultural context. The epistemic subject is not extended because of the casual coupling with external informational artifacts which extend his mind from inside the head and into the world. Rather, cognitive practices constitute the subject’s mind, they transform his cognitive abilities, and this is what makes the mind and epistemic subject “extended”.},
  abstract_source = {s2},
}

@article{merritt2011cure,
  author = {Merritt, Michele},
  title = {The cure for the cure: Networking the extended mind},
  journal = {Philosophical Psychology},
  year = {2011},
  volume = {24},
  pages = {463--485},
  doi = {10.1080/09515089.2011.580050},
  note = {
  CORE ARGUMENT: Merritt critiques narrow readings of extended mind theory
  that focus exclusively on individual-environment coupling, arguing for a
  networked approach that incorporates social and distributed dimensions.
  She examines how cognitive resources are networked across individuals and
  artifacts, creating extended systems that transcend simple dyadic coupling.
  This networking perspective reveals that cognitive extension often occurs
  through participation in socio-technical networks rather than individual
  tool use.

  RELEVANCE: This paper addresses limitations of focusing solely on
  individual cognitive offloading, highlighting the social and networked
  nature of extended cognitive systems. The networked perspective is
  relevant to understanding how cognitive offloading operates in
  collaborative contexts and through shared resources. This connects
  individual offloading practices to broader social and technological
  infrastructures.

  POSITION: Advocates networked approach to extended mind, transcending
  individual-environment coupling.
  },
  keywords = {networked-cognition, social-extension, distributed-cognition, Low},
  abstract = {Abstract The hypothesis of extended cognition (HEC), or the claim that cognitive processes are not entirely organism-bound and can extend into the world, has received a barrage of criticism. Likewise, defenders of HEC have responded and even retreated into more moderate positions. In this paper, I trace the debate, rehearsing what I take to be the three strongest cases against HEC: nonderived content, causally natural kinds, and informational integration. I then argue that so far, the replies have been unsatisfactory, mainly because they rest on tacit assumptions about the nature of "human organisms," which are the very subjects in question. One such reply, Clark's (2008) recent hypothesis of organism-centered cognition (HOC), is shown to be a particularly hasty retreat, specifically in terms of tackling the issue of informational integration. Namely, my position is that Clark concedes too quickly that the organism is the "chief executor" of this cognitive function and I claim this on the grounds that (1) not all human organisms integrate information in the way Weiskopf (2008 Weiskopf, D. 2008. Patrolling the mind's boundaries. Erkenntnis, 68(2): 265–276. [Crossref], [Web of Science ®] , [Google Scholar]) argues they do, and (2) it is not impossible for external tools to be an informationally integrative component of a "systemic whole." Keywords: Extended MindInformational IntegrationNonderived Content Notes Note [1] The "senior partner/equal partner" description is borrowed from Dan Hutto, personal communication.},
  abstract_source = {openalex},
}

@article{markic2017extended,
  author = {Marki\'{c}, Orsolya},
  title = {Extended Cognition: Feedback Loops and Coupled Systems},
  journal = {Interdisciplinary Description of Complex Systems},
  year = {2017},
  volume = {15},
  pages = {270--280},
  doi = {10.7906/INDECS.15.4.5},
  note = {
  CORE ARGUMENT: Marki\'{c} distinguishes two waves of active externalism:
  first-wave parity-based accounts and second-wave complementarity-based
  accounts. She analyzes how second-wave discussions focus on cognitive
  systems with feedback loops between internal and external elements,
  representing a more radical departure from functionalism. The
  complementarity principle addresses cognitive bloat and
  coupling-constitution objections by requiring productive differences
  rather than functional equivalence. She concludes with ethical
  considerations of extended cognition.

  RELEVANCE: This paper clarifies the shift from parity to complementarity
  in extended mind debates, directly relevant to understanding how
  integration approaches differ from earlier extended mind theories. The
  feedback loop emphasis highlights dynamic interaction rather than static
  coupling. The ethical dimension addresses normative questions about
  cognitive offloading often neglected in purely descriptive accounts.

  POSITION: Analyzes shift from parity to complementarity principles,
  emphasizing feedback loops and ethical implications.
  },
  keywords = {complementarity, feedback-loops, extended-mind-waves, Medium},
  abstract = {The article explores two waves of active externalism. I first introduce the distinction between passive and active externalism and analyse a proposal of active externalism based on the principle of parity proposed by Clark and Chalmers. There are two main obstacles, causal-constitution fallacy and cognitive bloat, that threaten the extended cognition hypothesis. The second wave of discussions based on the complementarity principle deals with cognitive systems with feedback loops between internal and external elements and is a more radical departure from functionalism and traditional thinking about cognition. I conclude with some remarks on potential ethical considerations of extended cognition.},
  abstract_source = {s2},
}

@article{fritzman2016is,
  author = {Fritzman, J. M. and Thornburg, Kristin},
  title = {``I Is Someone Else'': Constituting the Extended Mind's Fourth Wave, with Hegel},
  journal = {Essays in Philosophy},
  year = {2016},
  volume = {17},
  pages = {156--190},
  doi = {10.7710/1526-0569.1560},
  note = {
  CORE ARGUMENT: Fritzman and Thornburg propose a "fourth wave" of extended
  mind theory drawing on Hegelian philosophy. They argue that previous waves
  (parity, complementarity, integration) inadequately address how cognitive
  extension transforms personal identity and subjectivity. The Hegelian
  framework shows how mind extends through recognition by others and
  participation in social-cultural institutions, constituting rather than
  merely supporting selfhood. This provides a more robust account of how
  cognitive extension relates to personal identity.

  RELEVANCE: This paper addresses philosophical questions about how
  cognitive offloading relates to personal identity and selfhood, extending
  integration debates into metaphysics of mind. The Hegelian social-cultural
  dimension connects cognitive extension to institutional and historical
  structures. This is relevant to understanding whether and how cognitive
  offloading affects who we are, not just what we can do.

  POSITION: Proposes Hegelian fourth wave emphasizing how cognitive
  extension constitutes selfhood through social recognition.
  },
  keywords = {Hegelian-extension, personal-identity, fourth-wave, Low},
  abstract = {We seek to constitute the extended mind’s fourth wave, socially distributed group cognition, and we do so by thinking with Hegel. The extended mind theory’s first wave invokes the parity principle, which maintains that processes that occur external to the organism’s skin should be considered mental if they are regarded as mental when they occur inside the organism. The second wave appeals to the complementarity principle, which claims that what is crucial is that these processes together constitute a cognitive system. The first two waves assume that cognitive systems have well-defined territories or boundaries, and that internal and external processes do not switch location. The third wave rejects these assumptions, holding instead that internal processes are not privileged, and internal and external processes can switch, and that processes can be distributed among individuals. The fourth wave would advocate socially distributed group cognition. Groups are deterritorialized collective agents; they are ineliminatively and irreducibly real, they have mental states. Individuals constitute groups, but groups also constitute individuals. What counts as an individual and a group is a function of the level of analysis. And they are conflicted. Essays in Philosophy 17(2) 157 Essays Philos (2016)17:156-191 | DOI: 10.7710/1526-0569.1560 Published online: 8 July 2016. © Fritzman & Thornburg 2016 Contact authors: fritzman@lclark.edu, kristin.parvazian@gmail.com To work now? Never, never: I’m on strike. Right now, I’m encrapulating myself as much as possible. Why? I want to be a poet, and I’m working to turn myself into a seer: you won’t understand at all, and it’s unlikely that I’ll be able to explain it to you. It has to do with making your way toward the unknown by a derangement of all the senses. The suffering is tremendous, but one must bear up against it, to be born a poet, and I know that’s what I am. It’s not at all my fault. It’s wrong to say I think: one should say I am thought. Forgive the pun. I is someone else. Tough luck to the wood that becomes a violin, and to hell with the unaware who quibble over what they’re completely missing anyway!i dversaries of the extended mind emphasize the importance of the “persisting individual” to cognitive science. They urge that this is incompatible with the extended mind’s transient couplings and hook-ups, linking individuals and aspects of their environments, thereby constituting cognitive systems. Yet, in the nineteenth century, Arthur Rimbaud recognized that individuals are constitutively conjoined to others, always already, who are themselves so conjoined, and that an individual’s persistence is that of a A “I Is Someone Else” | Fritzman & Thornburg 158 continuing process, not a substance. Metaphor: individuals are not trees, much less petrified wood, but rhizomes.ii Asparagus and ginger are rhizomes, Indian lotus too. With uncanny insight, Hindus not only portray Viṣṇu (the god of preservation) and Lakṣmī (the goddess of prosperity) on lotuses, they also depict the universe’s creation as a lotus emerging from Viṣṇu’s navel. Although not his main point, Rimbaud saw that a violin constitutively depends on its wood. And, his main point: I does not think; rather, I is thought’s result. In the “Preface” to the Elements of the Philosophy of Right, Hegel cautions his readers to not expect philosophy to give advice about what should be done.iii This is so, he explains, because philosophy’s comprehension is always retrospective, discerning an era’s essential characteristics only after they have already fully developed. So, it might be anticipated that a project of thinking with Hegel about the extended mind could at most discern what others have already achieved— articulating, clarifying, and making explicit—but that it would not advance the discussion. The extended mind would clarify Hegel’s concept of Geist (“spirit” or “mind”), and his concept of “right” (Recht roughly, social mores and law) serves as an exemplar of the extended mind.iv This could seem like a system of mirrors, mutually illuminating each other— and impatient readers might wonder when the smoke will be introduced. Nevertheless, the project of making things explicit can be valuable, articulating and then synthesizing, thereby making way for further conceptual advance. Moreover, Hegelians have defended the extended mind from Mark Sprevak’s argument that the extended mind is overly permissive in its attributions of mental states, and that—since functionalism entails the extended mind—both should be rejected.v Essays in Philosophy 17(2) 159 Naturally, Hegelians worry, not that the extended mind is too liberal in its attributions of mental states, but rather that it is too conservative. We will discuss the extended mind’s first two waves, suggesting that they really constitute one wave, explain that the third wave is well under way, and show that the resources are in place for a fourth wave. We suggest that the fourth wave is conflicted, constituted, as it were, by various interfering waves.},
  abstract_source = {openalex},
}

